WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.520
Happy Thursday, everybody!

00:00:12.520 --> 00:00:15.440
Welcome to the Data Science Hangout.

00:00:15.440 --> 00:00:17.000
Hope everyone's having a great week.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:22.440
So the Data Science Hangout is our open space to chat about data science leadership, questions

00:00:22.440 --> 00:00:26.959
you're facing, and getting to hear about what's going on in the world of data across different

00:00:26.959 --> 00:00:27.959
industries.

00:00:27.959 --> 00:00:33.240
So it happens every Thursday at the same time, same place, so if you're ever watching these

00:00:33.240 --> 00:00:38.959
on YouTube, you can always add the calendar, there's a calendar link in the details below

00:00:38.959 --> 00:00:41.560
because we'd love to have you join us live too.

00:00:41.560 --> 00:00:47.799
But together, we're all dedicated to making this a welcoming environment for everyone.

00:00:47.799 --> 00:00:52.880
We love hearing from everybody, no matter your level of experience or area of work.

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:58.040
It is totally okay to just listen in if you want, but there's also three ways you can

00:00:58.040 --> 00:01:03.000
jump in and ask questions or provide your own perspective on certain topics.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:09.680
So you can jump in by raising your hand on Zoom, you can put questions in the Zoom chat,

00:01:09.680 --> 00:01:16.440
and feel free to just put a little star next to it if you want me to read it out as well.

00:01:16.440 --> 00:01:19.959
And then we also have a Slido link where you can ask questions anonymously, and I'm sure

00:01:20.080 --> 00:01:24.320
Hannah will share that in the chat here in just a second.

00:01:24.320 --> 00:01:30.239
So Eric said this would be a fun off-the-cuff session, we're doing things a little bit different

00:01:30.239 --> 00:01:31.239
today.

00:01:31.239 --> 00:01:36.720
So our featured leader for today was unfortunately sick, so we'll be rescheduling his session

00:01:36.720 --> 00:01:38.480
to the 18th.

00:01:38.480 --> 00:01:46.599
So for today, we are all the featured leaders, so we can all ask each other questions to

00:01:46.599 --> 00:01:49.760
the audience, so still ask questions the same way.

00:01:49.760 --> 00:01:55.040
But I was talking with a few of you an hour ago on LinkedIn, and both Libby and Mike said

00:01:55.040 --> 00:02:02.639
I should put myself in the hot seat here first, so I am happy to get started here.

00:02:02.639 --> 00:02:08.759
But I'm Rachel Dempsey, I lead our pro community at Posit, where I'm always looking for new

00:02:08.759 --> 00:02:14.639
ways to bring customers together and our community together, to be able to listen to feedback

00:02:14.759 --> 00:02:17.759
and learn from each other.

00:02:17.759 --> 00:02:23.839
To give you a little bit about my background here, so I've been at Posit for five and a

00:02:23.839 --> 00:02:29.759
half years, which I can't believe how fast that time has gone by.

00:02:29.759 --> 00:02:33.559
Of course, when I joined, it was RStudio.

00:02:33.559 --> 00:02:40.960
But I actually started off in sales, so I was working with our new professional customers,

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:45.960
and in those conversations with customers, people were always asking me, like, what are

00:02:45.960 --> 00:02:51.960
other people doing with your tools, or what are people doing in my industry?

00:02:51.960 --> 00:02:57.240
And we had some stories and customer stories on the site, but I didn't really have a great

00:02:57.240 --> 00:03:00.399
way to connect people.

00:03:00.399 --> 00:03:06.000
And I was just thinking about, like, all these amazing news cases and stories I was hearing

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:10.759
from other customer calls, but I couldn't say, like, hey, I just got off the call with

00:03:10.759 --> 00:03:13.679
so-and-so, this is what they're doing.

00:03:13.679 --> 00:03:19.839
So I started planning these enterprise community meetups a few years ago, because I was also

00:03:19.839 --> 00:03:25.720
running a Boston news hour group, and that actually helped me transition into the role

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:31.000
that I'm in now, so leading our professional community.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:36.880
And so that's just a little bit of background on my role, but outside of work, a few things

00:03:36.880 --> 00:03:39.240
that I like to do.

00:03:39.240 --> 00:03:41.479
So I like to play guitar.

00:03:41.479 --> 00:03:47.759
Not like professional or anything, but it's nice to be able to, like, get my mind off

00:03:47.759 --> 00:03:51.800
of work or outside, away from a screen.

00:03:51.800 --> 00:03:59.800
I like to run, snowboard, be active, do things outside.

00:03:59.800 --> 00:04:03.839
And it's been really fun getting to learn from you all, like, things that you do outside

00:04:03.839 --> 00:04:06.839
of your data world, too.

00:04:06.839 --> 00:04:09.479
But yeah, that's me.

00:04:09.479 --> 00:04:14.479
I'll kick things off here as our featured leader, but as I said, we're all the featured

00:04:14.479 --> 00:04:21.839
leaders today, so any questions that you have, still put them in the chat or on Slido.

00:04:21.839 --> 00:04:25.480
I can absolutely kick things off with starting talking about community.

00:04:25.480 --> 00:04:28.559
I love talking about community.

00:04:28.559 --> 00:04:34.559
So any questions you all have about that, happy to answer, too.

00:04:34.559 --> 00:04:35.559
Okay.

00:04:35.559 --> 00:04:42.760
Libby, I'm going to have you ask this question here live.

00:04:42.760 --> 00:04:43.760
I'm curious.

00:04:43.760 --> 00:04:46.559
I'm always curious about what people thought they would be doing when they were in high

00:04:46.559 --> 00:04:52.559
school versus what they're doing right now, because mine is so wildly different, because

00:04:52.559 --> 00:04:55.559
I feel like nobody in high school is like, I want to be an analyst or I want to be a

00:04:55.559 --> 00:04:57.239
data scientist.

00:04:57.239 --> 00:05:02.320
And community leader inside of a software, open source software company is like something

00:05:02.320 --> 00:05:05.239
you probably couldn't have imagined, right?

00:05:05.239 --> 00:05:06.239
Right.

00:05:06.239 --> 00:05:07.239
Absolutely.

00:05:07.239 --> 00:05:14.799
Um, I actually just very, I'm very indecisive, I like never knew exactly what I wanted to

00:05:14.799 --> 00:05:15.799
do.

00:05:15.799 --> 00:05:20.640
I wasn't one of those people who are like, yes, I want to be a doctor and I 100% know

00:05:20.640 --> 00:05:22.320
that.

00:05:22.320 --> 00:05:27.279
But it's, it's funny, I was thinking about this the other day, because I went to Bentley

00:05:27.279 --> 00:05:32.640
University of Business School, and my major was information design and corporate communication.

00:05:32.640 --> 00:05:39.440
I was thinking like, that's actually what I'm doing right now, which at the time, I

00:05:39.440 --> 00:05:44.480
didn't even know like, what those roles would be, when that was my major, and was thinking

00:05:44.480 --> 00:05:48.160
it was more like public relations.

00:05:48.160 --> 00:05:55.440
But something that I had shared at the RStudio conference last year is that I, I feel like

00:05:55.440 --> 00:06:01.640
a lot of, oh, Bill just sent, just put that in the chat, but a lot of what I know about

00:06:01.640 --> 00:06:06.399
community building has nothing to do with school or work.

00:06:06.399 --> 00:06:12.160
I shared in my conference talk that a lot of it actually came from watching my mom who's

00:06:12.320 --> 00:06:17.760
run a bar for 38 years, her and her friend own a bar in Groton, Connecticut.

00:06:18.480 --> 00:06:24.959
And so like, watching the way that my mom always interacted with customers, like new

00:06:24.959 --> 00:06:30.320
and regular customers, and how she'd always like walk up to every table and check on people

00:06:30.320 --> 00:06:35.519
and introduce herself, little things like that, like, always stuck in my mind.

00:06:35.519 --> 00:06:41.519
And I felt like they always came, like, it just felt like common sense or things that

00:06:41.519 --> 00:06:42.880
came natural to me.

00:06:42.880 --> 00:06:47.760
But then I realized in preparing for that conference talk, like, that really applies

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:49.519
to community building.

00:06:49.519 --> 00:06:56.399
I can share the, the blog post too, if anybody's ever curious or wants to check it out too.

00:07:00.160 --> 00:07:01.839
Anas, I see you have your hand raised.

00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:03.200
Yes.

00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:08.000
So, first of all, Rachel, thank you for sharing that.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:15.760
And I really think that some of those fields that relate to customer service, the skills

00:07:15.760 --> 00:07:19.920
are so transferable and, you know, you're applying it in different ways.

00:07:19.920 --> 00:07:23.839
You know, you see that restaurants, but you can apply it in everyday business settings.

00:07:23.839 --> 00:07:26.399
And I, I think that's very powerful.

00:07:26.399 --> 00:07:31.600
Myself, personally, I've had roles in food service, and I feel like I carry that wherever

00:07:31.600 --> 00:07:31.920
I go.

00:07:32.720 --> 00:07:36.720
But a question or a topic I want to open to the community, if possible.

00:07:38.559 --> 00:07:46.959
So, I'm not sure here on this call, if anyone has, within a large enterprise, been part

00:07:46.959 --> 00:07:59.119
of the initiation of using our solutions or our tools, essentially, that, that I find

00:07:59.119 --> 00:08:05.519
myself in my, in my current role, you know, in big organizations, it's a little bit harder

00:08:05.519 --> 00:08:09.440
to get that traction or get that momentum or get that trust.

00:08:10.079 --> 00:08:14.640
And I'm curious if, if anyone on the call has thoughts or ideas to share about, about

00:08:14.640 --> 00:08:21.119
that topic, or what have they done, or how have they, how have they implemented using

00:08:21.119 --> 00:08:27.040
our more, more openly or more commonly in, in these larger organizations?

00:08:28.559 --> 00:08:29.359
Absolutely.

00:08:29.359 --> 00:08:34.799
I see Eric has some thoughts on this, on this issue, if you want to start.

00:08:34.799 --> 00:08:37.679
And anybody else who has thoughts, feel free to just raise your hand here too.

00:08:38.479 --> 00:08:38.880
Yeah.

00:08:38.880 --> 00:08:44.400
I mean, it's a very important issue and some I wrestled with my early career.

00:08:44.400 --> 00:08:49.440
I touched a little bit on this, I think, in the hangout from last year, but I think for

00:08:49.440 --> 00:08:57.039
me, what drove it to leadership, the value of what open source could bring is, I hate

00:08:57.039 --> 00:09:01.119
to say, I kind of took matters into my own hands in one way by spinning up the infrastructure

00:09:01.119 --> 00:09:06.080
myself with a little help from IT to get the, you know, the RStudio server and Shiny

00:09:06.080 --> 00:09:07.440
server spun up.

00:09:07.440 --> 00:09:14.400
And I just show them a couple simple prototypes, nothing that fancy by today's standards, but

00:09:14.400 --> 00:09:16.559
then it just organically grew.

00:09:16.559 --> 00:09:21.919
So I was kind of like in sports, some of my favorite people I follow in the sports world,

00:09:21.919 --> 00:09:22.960
they'll lead by example.

00:09:22.960 --> 00:09:26.960
They're not going to shout at teammates about, oh, you did bad, or this is what we need to

00:09:26.960 --> 00:09:27.440
do.

00:09:27.440 --> 00:09:28.719
They just go and do it.

00:09:28.719 --> 00:09:30.719
And then they kind of bring people along the way.

00:09:30.719 --> 00:09:36.880
So I took a calculated risk at the time I was sewing on it and realized how risky it

00:09:36.880 --> 00:09:39.919
was until after the fact, but it ended up working.

00:09:39.919 --> 00:09:46.320
So I think leading by example and trying to get some examples to leadership of like, this

00:09:46.320 --> 00:09:52.400
is what is possible, but in order to make this happen, you need some support to push

00:09:52.400 --> 00:09:53.039
it further.

00:09:53.039 --> 00:09:59.919
But just getting those examples in the right eyes of people that are ready to embrace doing

00:09:59.919 --> 00:10:05.200
something new, not always following on the status quo way of doing things.

00:10:05.200 --> 00:10:07.039
I think that's my general advice.

00:10:07.039 --> 00:10:09.440
Thanks, Eric.

00:10:09.440 --> 00:10:12.080
I see Zach, you have your hand raised too, if you want to jump in here.

00:10:14.080 --> 00:10:15.919
Yeah, so I'm going to match Eric.

00:10:16.559 --> 00:10:23.359
I was the IT guy that would help somebody like Eric stand up the infrastructure and kind

00:10:23.359 --> 00:10:26.960
of present the need to the leadership team, right?

00:10:27.919 --> 00:10:34.559
I handled a big project for a small, very small life science organization many years

00:10:34.559 --> 00:10:37.280
ago where it was a computational chemist.

00:10:37.280 --> 00:10:38.960
I was like, hey, here's the tools we need.

00:10:38.960 --> 00:10:42.960
Here's the space we need to kind of pitch to the organization.

00:10:42.960 --> 00:10:48.559
And present day, they've got a data center and multiple Novaceks, right?

00:10:48.559 --> 00:10:52.479
And many different data analysts running their pipeline that they built on R.

00:10:52.479 --> 00:10:55.280
And so I think it absolutely takes a tribe.

00:10:57.520 --> 00:11:00.320
Thank you both.

00:11:00.320 --> 00:11:00.960
Thank you both.

00:11:00.960 --> 00:11:01.280
Yeah.

00:11:01.280 --> 00:11:01.520
Sorry.

00:11:01.520 --> 00:11:02.239
I'll thank you both.

00:11:04.559 --> 00:11:08.559
I see Marlene has a great question in the chat in a thread.

00:11:08.559 --> 00:11:12.719
Everybody's starting about what profession you envisioned yourself in high school.

00:11:15.280 --> 00:11:17.039
I see you.

00:11:17.039 --> 00:11:20.159
You had asked a question to the audience here.

00:11:20.159 --> 00:11:22.000
Do you want to jump in and ask that?

00:11:23.039 --> 00:11:23.679
Sure.

00:11:23.679 --> 00:11:24.559
So hi, everyone.

00:11:24.559 --> 00:11:31.280
I'm just wondering, so far, what is the company's response to chatGPT?

00:11:32.159 --> 00:11:36.159
Any company has any concrete plan to use it to create value for the business?

00:11:36.799 --> 00:11:40.000
Right now, we are having some weekly meetings on chatGPT.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:42.960
We discuss how to use it for our business.

00:11:42.960 --> 00:11:44.559
We are a financial service company.

00:11:44.559 --> 00:11:48.320
So for us, transparency is very important.

00:11:48.320 --> 00:11:51.520
The model needs to be interpretable and explainable.

00:11:51.520 --> 00:11:54.239
So we cannot use it directly, obviously.

00:11:54.799 --> 00:12:00.400
We cannot give any of our customer data to the server of open chatGPT to rate it,

00:12:00.400 --> 00:12:02.000
and they cannot respond.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:05.679
So we are planning to build our in-house, a similar in-house model.

00:12:05.679 --> 00:12:10.400
Here, I'm just wondering, any company here have any concrete plan on chatGPT?

00:12:10.400 --> 00:12:11.440
How do we use it for the business?

00:12:15.359 --> 00:12:17.119
You had to throw a hard one in there, you.

00:12:18.799 --> 00:12:21.200
Anybody have thoughts?

00:12:21.200 --> 00:12:22.719
I don't have a great answer.

00:12:22.719 --> 00:12:24.000
We're all trying to figure it out.

00:12:24.799 --> 00:12:31.440
But I can share that in our internal company, our first meet over the year was one of my

00:12:31.440 --> 00:12:36.559
colleagues showing how they were using chatGPT as their virtual code assistant to build a

00:12:36.559 --> 00:12:38.000
Shiny app quite quickly.

00:12:38.719 --> 00:12:40.479
And everybody was blown away.

00:12:40.479 --> 00:12:41.919
It actually wasn't too bad.

00:12:43.039 --> 00:12:46.479
Much better than the last time I tried something like this, a co-pilot, about a year and a

00:12:46.479 --> 00:12:47.039
half ago.

00:12:47.840 --> 00:12:53.760
We're seeing potential as that virtual pair programmer that you can bounce ideas off of,

00:12:53.760 --> 00:12:56.719
maybe for a language you're not as familiar with.

00:12:56.719 --> 00:13:01.119
Like for me, I'm still on this JavaScript learning journey, even though I've been using

00:13:01.119 --> 00:13:03.039
Shiny since the very beginning.

00:13:03.039 --> 00:13:07.599
I've been able to be a consumer of Shiny without having to know too much about the nuts and

00:13:07.599 --> 00:13:08.320
bolts behind it.

00:13:08.320 --> 00:13:13.599
But now I've kind of taken that extra transition to having to extend it a bit more.

00:13:13.599 --> 00:13:16.479
So that's how we're starting with it.

00:13:16.479 --> 00:13:21.520
But in my industry of life sciences, we have to be, I hate to say it, pretty cautious about

00:13:21.520 --> 00:13:22.799
how we're using this.

00:13:22.880 --> 00:13:28.640
But we are very much intrigued by what it can do from an efficiency standpoint, for

00:13:28.640 --> 00:13:29.280
sure.

00:13:29.280 --> 00:13:33.440
Yeah, I see a lot of thoughts here in the chat about it too.

00:13:33.440 --> 00:13:36.799
I think Marlene, you weighed in first about this.

00:13:36.799 --> 00:13:37.520
Do you want to jump in?

00:13:42.320 --> 00:13:46.880
So everybody asks me, because I'm the one data scientist in our family of companies,

00:13:47.520 --> 00:13:49.679
what's the dealio with chatGPT?

00:13:49.679 --> 00:13:52.239
And overall, I try to say it's a tool, right?

00:13:53.280 --> 00:13:57.840
With a pencil, you can draw, you can write prose, you could dab somebody.

00:13:57.840 --> 00:14:02.400
So I keep telling them it's just like any other tool, depends on how it's wielded.

00:14:02.400 --> 00:14:07.119
But so far, the biggest non-supporters of it has been the communications department.

00:14:07.919 --> 00:14:10.159
Anybody in journalism is very threatened by it.

00:14:10.880 --> 00:14:13.919
But I keep trying to tell them it's great for brainstorming.

00:14:13.919 --> 00:14:17.760
Don't think of it as like polished copyright, you know?

00:14:18.640 --> 00:14:19.280
So it's funny.

00:14:19.280 --> 00:14:22.719
I think you're going to end up being, each one of you, you're going to end up having

00:14:22.799 --> 00:14:26.880
a lot of people come to you and trying to be seen as an expert, right?

00:14:28.479 --> 00:14:29.599
A domain expert in it.

00:14:30.719 --> 00:14:34.479
Always, my advice to you especially, try to be objective, right?

00:14:34.479 --> 00:14:36.320
Even though you have your own opinions about it,

00:14:37.599 --> 00:14:40.239
it's important for us to be good stewards of knowledge.

00:14:41.119 --> 00:14:45.919
So I do my best to tell people, like, envision a lot, be cautious,

00:14:45.919 --> 00:14:49.760
but also, like, feel free to dream because it's not going away.

00:14:49.760 --> 00:14:54.000
So that's kind of been my message to anybody who's asked in my company,

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:57.039
which has been a lot in the last couple weeks, that's for sure.

00:14:57.039 --> 00:14:58.239
So that's my two cents.

00:14:58.960 --> 00:15:01.119
My message is always talk to legal.

00:15:03.280 --> 00:15:07.200
I know there are a lot of concerns about not only, obviously,

00:15:07.200 --> 00:15:08.320
sending your data to their servers,

00:15:08.320 --> 00:15:11.520
but even if you have like a local instance of a model running,

00:15:11.520 --> 00:15:13.840
there's always concern about bias in the model.

00:15:13.840 --> 00:15:16.320
And there's always concern about some of the copyright stuff.

00:15:16.320 --> 00:15:19.280
So if you're producing code and then using it,

00:15:19.840 --> 00:15:21.039
you know, where did that code come from?

00:15:21.039 --> 00:15:23.520
That's all obfuscated behind the model.

00:15:23.520 --> 00:15:26.880
So I definitely, I'm so excited about the tech.

00:15:26.880 --> 00:15:30.400
I know people in my company are, but gosh, everyone has to be so careful.

00:15:30.400 --> 00:15:38.799
We learned from Samsung who's shared a bunch of sensitive information with a model,

00:15:38.799 --> 00:15:40.559
and now it's all out in public domain.

00:15:40.559 --> 00:15:41.359
So be careful.

00:15:41.760 --> 00:15:42.260
Yeah.

00:15:42.960 --> 00:15:49.679
I see, Andy, you put a thought about how you might be using ChatGPT.

00:15:49.679 --> 00:15:50.640
Do you want to jump in there?

00:15:54.239 --> 00:15:54.719
Yeah, sure.

00:15:55.280 --> 00:15:57.599
So I work for Teach for America as a data scientist.

00:15:57.599 --> 00:16:00.960
So we have 10,000 applications coming every year,

00:16:00.960 --> 00:16:04.000
and we do a first pass with our NLP models.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:05.599
But we've had this huge challenge now,

00:16:05.599 --> 00:16:10.000
because we are the target audience for the early adopters of GPT,

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:13.520
which is like college age students who are writing essays.

00:16:13.520 --> 00:16:17.359
And because we're basically have trained college age students

00:16:17.359 --> 00:16:20.719
to write the exact same essay that GPT wants to write,

00:16:20.719 --> 00:16:22.559
we're now dealing with this huge repercussion of

00:16:23.200 --> 00:16:31.119
all of our historical training datasets for NLP parsing are trained prior to GPT.

00:16:31.119 --> 00:16:32.640
And now we have this huge influx.

00:16:32.640 --> 00:16:35.760
So it's really become a challenge, you know, not on,

00:16:35.760 --> 00:16:41.359
we also use GPT internally, but it's more on like the receiving end

00:16:41.359 --> 00:16:44.080
of seeing the products of GPT has been a huge challenge.

00:16:46.080 --> 00:16:46.559
Thank you.

00:16:47.520 --> 00:16:51.119
I see, Mike, you had a question earlier.

00:16:51.119 --> 00:16:53.520
It's funny to be like, hey, Mike, you had a question for me.

00:16:53.520 --> 00:16:54.400
Can you ask it?

00:16:55.919 --> 00:16:57.280
Hey, Rachel, how would you like to be?

00:16:58.080 --> 00:17:01.599
I asked you in the chat was basically you were,

00:17:01.599 --> 00:17:05.439
I know that you, you know, have come from a marketing background.

00:17:06.160 --> 00:17:12.400
And so, you know, oftentimes I've, I've said that data scientists are geeks,

00:17:12.400 --> 00:17:15.680
you know, and so if we're selling to people that selling to other geeks

00:17:15.680 --> 00:17:18.800
and we're trying to hook them in with how clever the solution is or how,

00:17:19.439 --> 00:17:24.719
you know, how, you know, what, how it's going to help us do geeky stuff better.

00:17:26.239 --> 00:17:28.160
Well, knowing about marketing,

00:17:29.040 --> 00:17:33.359
what skills would you recommend data scientists to look into

00:17:33.359 --> 00:17:37.119
for selling upwards to managers and people who aren't the geeks?

00:17:38.880 --> 00:17:39.380
Yeah.

00:17:40.640 --> 00:17:44.719
So something I think that is really important is like

00:17:44.719 --> 00:17:48.560
actually taking the time to make something look pretty.

00:17:49.520 --> 00:17:53.599
And there's a lot of tools out there that you can use to do that.

00:17:53.599 --> 00:17:58.160
One that I always use for like meetup groups is Canva

00:17:58.719 --> 00:18:01.680
because there's like a bunch of different like design templates.

00:18:02.479 --> 00:18:06.560
But I always find if you put like a little bit of effort into what something

00:18:07.359 --> 00:18:09.920
looks like, people take it more seriously.

00:18:11.439 --> 00:18:18.079
And so I was thinking about that with like showing an idea for an app to

00:18:19.680 --> 00:18:26.079
your leadership team, like trying to like actually use the colors that match your brand

00:18:26.079 --> 00:18:30.719
or putting your logo in it so that people immediately see it as something like,

00:18:30.719 --> 00:18:33.760
oh, this is how we would use this at our company.

00:18:33.760 --> 00:18:40.640
Even if it's completely made up data, I think having the brand guidelines there,

00:18:40.640 --> 00:18:43.680
like it just changes the way people view it.

00:18:46.640 --> 00:18:49.119
That's one thing I've been thinking about.

00:18:50.239 --> 00:18:54.880
But I, I mean, I still struggle with this too, like pushing ideas forward.

00:18:54.880 --> 00:18:59.839
I literally just got off a call about something a little bit, probably an hour ago.

00:19:01.599 --> 00:19:09.119
And one mistake I made was like not thinking of the sales process with my own idea.

00:19:10.400 --> 00:19:16.560
Like if I get really excited about something, I want to go like make it happen immediately.

00:19:16.560 --> 00:19:22.239
And sometimes that's good, but sometimes you need to make sure that you are actually like

00:19:23.280 --> 00:19:29.280
bringing everybody on board to see your vision and your goal for the project.

00:19:30.880 --> 00:19:35.920
Especially in leadership so that they can help push it forward.

00:19:35.920 --> 00:19:39.040
Because I've learned like you're not always going to be in the room when

00:19:39.040 --> 00:19:40.800
somebody is discussing your ideas.

00:19:41.439 --> 00:19:43.520
So it's important like they understand it too.

00:19:47.520 --> 00:19:48.020
Thanks.

00:19:49.040 --> 00:19:49.680
Does that help?

00:19:52.319 --> 00:19:54.319
Are you looking for a different direction there?

00:19:54.640 --> 00:20:02.319
Well, it's, it's kind of, there's the, I guess, there's several directions I was thinking.

00:20:02.319 --> 00:20:09.680
One is, we have a good solution or we've got a good idea that we want to kind of get management

00:20:09.680 --> 00:20:12.400
buy in from, right, which is a tricky process.

00:20:12.400 --> 00:20:17.359
And, you know, there's a, you get a limited amount of their time.

00:20:17.359 --> 00:20:21.280
So how do you ensure that, you know, all the things they want to know are ticked?

00:20:21.280 --> 00:20:24.800
There's another question, which is possibly for a different day, but it's more,

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:27.839
you're trying to sell to your peers.

00:20:27.839 --> 00:20:32.000
So to other data scientists, Hey, we've got a process well-defined here.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:37.280
How many times do you, and then how many ways do you keep telling them that same thing?

00:20:37.280 --> 00:20:38.319
So that the time drops.

00:20:41.359 --> 00:20:41.859
Yeah.

00:20:42.400 --> 00:20:47.760
I mean, a piece of advice I can share here just from like community building and also

00:20:47.760 --> 00:20:48.800
getting everybody on board.

00:20:49.199 --> 00:20:55.520
Like community building and also getting our, getting our team on board to come to events

00:20:55.520 --> 00:21:02.719
as well as just having one-on-one conversations with people to learn about some of the problems

00:21:02.719 --> 00:21:05.680
that they're facing every day in their work.

00:21:05.680 --> 00:21:10.880
And then trying to incorporate that into whatever you are proposing.

00:21:11.839 --> 00:21:19.199
So that you can like build them up as your own champions to help you like pushing this

00:21:19.199 --> 00:21:19.699
forward.

00:21:21.760 --> 00:21:25.119
That's been, that's been really helpful for me.

00:21:25.119 --> 00:21:29.680
I know it's kind of trying to compare like two different things here, cause I'm not a

00:21:29.680 --> 00:21:36.800
data scientist pushing this forward, but maybe even just thinking about like pushing the

00:21:36.800 --> 00:21:41.920
data science hangout forward and making sure that people see the value in that too.

00:21:45.040 --> 00:21:51.119
Any of anybody else have thoughts on, on this and kind of selling to the leadership and

00:21:51.119 --> 00:21:51.920
sharing your ideas?

00:21:54.800 --> 00:21:59.439
I will say that getting to know people on a more personal level is really helpful.

00:21:59.439 --> 00:22:04.479
Like if you can have conversations with leadership that are not about work and get to know them

00:22:04.479 --> 00:22:07.280
and what matters to them generally in life.

00:22:07.280 --> 00:22:14.000
And even what matters to them in a business sense, everybody has a different thing that

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:17.680
they're championing and that they're really interested in moving forward.

00:22:17.680 --> 00:22:22.400
And so finding out what is individually motivating these people that you're trying to talk to

00:22:22.400 --> 00:22:26.800
can be really helpful because then you can speak to that and you're not just blowing

00:22:26.800 --> 00:22:28.479
your own, own horn a bunch, right?

00:22:28.479 --> 00:22:30.079
Like you can blow their horn.

00:22:30.079 --> 00:22:32.079
I think that that's really helpful and important.

00:22:33.040 --> 00:22:33.599
Absolutely.

00:22:34.719 --> 00:22:39.439
And I, I've been trying to take some of the advice that you all share here too, and all

00:22:39.439 --> 00:22:40.560
the different future leaders.

00:22:40.560 --> 00:22:48.959
And I remember like, I think Emmy Zimbardo was sharing about like repeating the things

00:22:48.959 --> 00:22:56.160
that you really care about and not, not just thinking because you said something or propose

00:22:57.119 --> 00:23:02.079
something as an idea one time that it's going to be accepted.

00:23:02.079 --> 00:23:03.680
Like you have to keep talking about it.

00:23:05.760 --> 00:23:13.520
And then I've also been trying to put my ideas in the lens of our like company OKRs or objectives

00:23:13.520 --> 00:23:19.599
and key results so that when they're talking about those at a leadership level that they

00:23:19.599 --> 00:23:25.520
think about my project because it was put into those exact words or those terms.

00:23:26.160 --> 00:23:31.359
Anas, I see you have your hand raised.

00:23:31.359 --> 00:23:38.560
Yeah, just a little, I guess in addition to that piece of advice, I would say that when

00:23:38.560 --> 00:23:43.599
speaking with leaders, sometimes saying less is more.

00:23:44.319 --> 00:23:52.239
We tend to overshare the technical aspects and we're very, and sometimes we feel the

00:23:52.239 --> 00:23:59.599
need to talk into those details to make our point, but they're not as interested in the

00:23:59.599 --> 00:24:04.719
technical pieces, just, you know, speak to them, you know, at a normal human level and

00:24:04.719 --> 00:24:06.000
they trust you as an expert.

00:24:06.719 --> 00:24:07.839
There is that aspect.

00:24:08.719 --> 00:24:12.560
You just have to come from their angle as much as possible but I feel like that's something

00:24:12.560 --> 00:24:17.040
I've learned more recently when I'm explaining a model or I'm explaining a solution I feel

00:24:17.040 --> 00:24:20.719
like I want to go into some of the technical details where it's like that's not, they're

00:24:20.719 --> 00:24:25.199
not too worried about that piece, they're just worried about the, how does this impact

00:24:25.199 --> 00:24:26.959
them or how is this going to impact the organization.

00:24:29.760 --> 00:24:30.400
Definitely.

00:24:31.439 --> 00:24:37.599
Caitlin, I see you just put an example into the chat if you want to weigh in here.

00:24:38.959 --> 00:24:39.680
Yeah, sure.

00:24:39.680 --> 00:24:45.920
So, I was just saying, at my old company, I did end up pitching data for good center

00:24:45.920 --> 00:24:50.959
of excellence and it took a few pitch decks that I made on campus, by the way.

00:24:52.560 --> 00:24:58.800
But no, I think the biggest feedback I got from that is just echoing what Anna said here.

00:24:59.680 --> 00:25:03.920
Don't try and be technical with non-technical people like that's truly not what they care

00:25:03.920 --> 00:25:10.239
about and I think putting yourself in the shoes of whoever you're pitching to is so

00:25:10.239 --> 00:25:16.319
important and focusing not on the outcomes like for yourself or like I want to do this

00:25:16.319 --> 00:25:21.520
idea because xyz is my passion, like they don't really care that that's your passion

00:25:21.520 --> 00:25:26.479
so much but they want to know how it's going to help them actually, not how it's going

00:25:26.479 --> 00:25:28.000
to help you in your career in your future.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:33.439
But so yeah, I ended up doing a couple of pitch decks, definitely a lot of meetings

00:25:33.439 --> 00:25:37.839
and then I think something that's really helpful for higher ups to see is almost like

00:25:37.839 --> 00:25:43.439
a 30, 60, 90 day plan on like what the outcomes may be of your idea.

00:25:46.239 --> 00:25:47.760
That's really helpful, thanks Caitlin.

00:25:49.920 --> 00:25:56.719
I see there was a question in the chat if there's like a slack or discord or some group

00:25:57.280 --> 00:26:02.560
for everybody to connect after the fact with the hangouts or where to find the hangout recordings.

00:26:03.280 --> 00:26:06.800
I see Libby mentioned the YouTube.

00:26:06.800 --> 00:26:11.359
If anybody wants to share the YouTube playlist where all the recordings are that would be

00:26:11.359 --> 00:26:18.400
super helpful but right now we don't have a great like solution for like the ongoing

00:26:18.400 --> 00:26:19.119
conversations.

00:26:19.119 --> 00:26:21.920
I would love to have that in the future.

00:26:21.920 --> 00:26:26.160
Right now we just have a LinkedIn group which I'll share here.

00:26:26.880 --> 00:26:32.160
I know that's not the best format for having conversation sometimes but it's what we have

00:26:32.239 --> 00:26:32.959
right now.

00:26:32.959 --> 00:26:36.479
But we can definitely explore other options there too.

00:26:39.280 --> 00:26:45.199
A Slido question that was asked is for the whole audience, do you have any favorite data

00:26:45.199 --> 00:26:47.680
science podcasts or YouTube channels?

00:26:52.640 --> 00:26:54.319
I see a lot being shared.

00:26:54.319 --> 00:26:56.719
Data humans, Libby's podcast, absolutely.

00:26:57.839 --> 00:26:59.599
I'll be myself in AI too.

00:26:59.599 --> 00:27:00.719
I find it pretty interesting.

00:27:00.719 --> 00:27:05.439
They just recently had a couple from, one was an airline.

00:27:05.439 --> 00:27:10.160
I think it was, I want to say it was Delta and then another from Lego group.

00:27:10.160 --> 00:27:16.479
So as a Lego nerd, that was also really cool to see data science and AI and Lego and things

00:27:16.479 --> 00:27:16.880
like that.

00:27:18.079 --> 00:27:18.719
That's cool.

00:27:19.599 --> 00:27:21.599
Thank you all for sharing them in the chat too.

00:27:21.599 --> 00:27:23.520
We'll have to go collect all these.

00:27:23.520 --> 00:27:25.119
Mike, I see you have your hand raised.

00:27:25.359 --> 00:27:31.599
I mean, we can't talk about data humans with Libby on this call without Libby giving us

00:27:31.599 --> 00:27:34.079
the elevator pitch of what data humans is about.

00:27:34.079 --> 00:27:34.719
Yes, absolutely.

00:27:37.599 --> 00:27:38.400
I would be happy to.

00:27:39.760 --> 00:27:41.760
Data humans doesn't have a ton of episodes.

00:27:41.760 --> 00:27:43.520
It's something I'm doing on the side.

00:27:43.520 --> 00:27:48.400
It's like every month or six weeks whenever I can get it in and convince somebody to come

00:27:48.400 --> 00:27:49.040
on the podcast.

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:56.719
But I started it because I realized that there was a lack of vulnerability and realness when

00:27:56.719 --> 00:27:59.359
a lot of people, especially people on LinkedIn are talking about data science.

00:27:59.359 --> 00:28:02.719
It's like all wins, all I'm doing this big, huge modeling thing.

00:28:02.719 --> 00:28:06.560
And when you meet them, sometimes you realize they aren't actually doing that for work.

00:28:06.560 --> 00:28:07.839
They're doing that on the side for fun.

00:28:08.800 --> 00:28:13.439
Not everybody is a full-time R package developer.

00:28:14.160 --> 00:28:19.760
It kind of has the potential to make us all feel like everybody else is doing something

00:28:19.760 --> 00:28:21.119
so much cooler than we are.

00:28:21.119 --> 00:28:25.599
They must be doing something so much cooler than what I'm doing, because what I'm doing

00:28:25.599 --> 00:28:26.959
is like a bunch of Excel still.

00:28:26.959 --> 00:28:31.839
And my company doesn't want to have a code-first approach to analytics and all this stuff.

00:28:33.359 --> 00:28:36.079
And really, we're all pretty similar.

00:28:36.079 --> 00:28:42.000
On the whole, there's still a ton of data people using Excel and using SAS and using

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:45.520
things that are not crazy, huge machine learning models.

00:28:45.520 --> 00:28:51.599
So I just wanted a place to talk to everyday data people, like not CEOs, right?

00:28:51.599 --> 00:28:57.359
Because there's a ton of podcasts that are CEOs or super senior data scientists at Spotify

00:28:57.359 --> 00:28:58.000
or whatever it is.

00:28:58.000 --> 00:28:59.199
And that's fantastic.

00:28:59.199 --> 00:29:00.959
Learning from those people is great.

00:29:00.959 --> 00:29:08.239
But what I'm interested in is the everyday people like me and people who are just doing

00:29:08.239 --> 00:29:08.719
normal stuff.

00:29:08.719 --> 00:29:09.439
What are they doing?

00:29:09.439 --> 00:29:12.719
We don't get a peek behind that vulnerable curtain very often.

00:29:14.160 --> 00:29:17.199
And then, of course, Eric is also on this call.

00:29:17.199 --> 00:29:19.439
Eric was the first podcast I ever listened to.

00:29:19.439 --> 00:29:21.760
When I first started learning R, I felt really alone.

00:29:21.760 --> 00:29:26.400
I'm like, there's no way that anybody else is this excited about a programming language

00:29:26.400 --> 00:29:26.959
as I am.

00:29:26.959 --> 00:29:30.880
I'm sitting there in my first R programming class.

00:29:30.880 --> 00:29:32.000
Everybody's really bored.

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:33.280
I'm super excited.

00:29:33.280 --> 00:29:35.359
I have a copy of the grammar of graphics.

00:29:35.359 --> 00:29:38.959
I am absolutely just highly invested in this thing.

00:29:38.959 --> 00:29:40.239
And I found Eric's podcast.

00:29:40.239 --> 00:29:42.560
And I was like, there are other people out there like me.

00:29:47.040 --> 00:29:47.760
Thank you, Libby.

00:29:47.760 --> 00:29:51.280
And Eric, now we're going to have to have you give a little overview too.

00:29:52.560 --> 00:29:53.359
It's amazing.

00:29:53.359 --> 00:29:58.959
That's why I started the whole thing is I wanted to connect with people.

00:29:58.959 --> 00:30:06.400
And I cannot think of a better thing I could have done, even though I was really running

00:30:06.400 --> 00:30:08.959
with no knowledge of how to do any of this whatsoever.

00:30:08.959 --> 00:30:13.119
But no, really, it's about connecting with people.

00:30:13.119 --> 00:30:18.640
But I'm really passionate about sharing what other people are doing that I'm learning from

00:30:18.640 --> 00:30:19.199
every day.

00:30:19.199 --> 00:30:24.719
And so that's why the R Weekly Project, once I got involved with that, I realized, well,

00:30:24.719 --> 00:30:26.000
yeah, we have the website.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:27.439
Every week, we have a new issue.

00:30:27.439 --> 00:30:32.079
But let's have another avenue to deliver this great content out there.

00:30:32.079 --> 00:30:35.199
And that's why I started the R Weekly Highlights.

00:30:35.199 --> 00:30:37.599
And it's been a joy to work with.

00:30:38.160 --> 00:30:39.359
I cannot do it alone.

00:30:39.359 --> 00:30:40.479
I say this every week.

00:30:41.040 --> 00:30:45.599
So Mike Thomas, my co-host here, is one of the biggest motivators for me to keep going

00:30:45.599 --> 00:30:47.280
because it's a weekly show.

00:30:47.280 --> 00:30:48.800
We have a day job with kids.

00:30:48.800 --> 00:30:50.000
It is a lot to fit in.

00:30:50.000 --> 00:30:52.479
But R is my hobby.

00:30:52.479 --> 00:30:54.560
I'm still open sources.

00:30:54.560 --> 00:30:55.119
My jam.

00:30:55.119 --> 00:30:56.560
I love talking about it.

00:30:56.560 --> 00:30:59.760
So just throw it out there, see if it resonates.

00:30:59.760 --> 00:31:00.800
And sure enough, it has.

00:31:00.800 --> 00:31:05.119
But yeah, I love hearing the stories and being able to put the spotlight on

00:31:05.119 --> 00:31:07.119
others in the community that are doing awesome things.

00:31:07.119 --> 00:31:08.719
So it's a true pleasure to do.

00:31:11.760 --> 00:31:16.239
This feels like such a heartwarming community call right now.

00:31:16.239 --> 00:31:22.400
And I just wanted to take an opportunity to say thank you to everybody here who has also

00:31:22.400 --> 00:31:25.199
helped make this space what it is.

00:31:25.199 --> 00:31:29.680
And I absolutely love getting to hang out with you all every Thursday.

00:31:29.680 --> 00:31:34.800
And if I think back to it, I think we're going on about two years in a month or so.

00:31:35.280 --> 00:31:37.199
Which is amazing.

00:31:37.920 --> 00:31:42.640
But if I think back to two years ago, and I thought we didn't have a featured leader,

00:31:42.640 --> 00:31:45.839
and we were just going to join and all chat, I would be freaking out.

00:31:47.119 --> 00:31:51.839
And I just love that we're all able to have this open conversation here.

00:31:51.839 --> 00:31:54.560
So I just want to say thank you to all of you here, too.

00:31:55.119 --> 00:31:56.160
Thank you, Rachel.

00:31:56.800 --> 00:31:58.239
Everybody, round of applause for Rachel.

00:31:59.439 --> 00:32:01.439
You're our fearless leader, whether you know it or not.

00:32:02.479 --> 00:32:02.959
Thank you.

00:32:03.760 --> 00:32:09.599
Rory, I see you had some thoughts on something we were talking about a little bit earlier

00:32:09.599 --> 00:32:11.439
on the topic of spreading ideas.

00:32:11.439 --> 00:32:12.479
Do you want to jump in here?

00:32:15.520 --> 00:32:15.920
Sure.

00:32:15.920 --> 00:32:16.719
Can you guys hear me?

00:32:16.719 --> 00:32:19.839
I just hadn't had audio or video on.

00:32:19.839 --> 00:32:20.479
Yes, they can.

00:32:21.199 --> 00:32:22.959
Yeah, just a little background.

00:32:22.959 --> 00:32:26.640
So I work as a behavior scientist.

00:32:26.640 --> 00:32:32.239
And my big interest is in organizational network analysis and a lot of relationship dynamics.

00:32:32.959 --> 00:32:37.119
In organizations, and I think one of the things that doesn't often get talked about

00:32:37.119 --> 00:32:43.280
is how the relationships that you have are really important with influencing people and

00:32:43.280 --> 00:32:44.000
getting buy-in.

00:32:44.959 --> 00:32:51.119
And one of my sort of favorite resources or people to follow is this guy named Mike Arena,

00:32:51.119 --> 00:32:54.800
who used to be at AWS leading their talent organization.

00:32:56.400 --> 00:33:01.359
And he has recently done a lot of research on remote work, on hybrid work, on

00:33:02.160 --> 00:33:04.079
relationships and innovation.

00:33:04.079 --> 00:33:10.000
And he's generally found for a lot of that research that it's best to spend a lot of

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:11.359
time incubating your ideas.

00:33:11.359 --> 00:33:14.719
If you come up with an idea, you're passionate about it, kind of like you were talking about,

00:33:14.719 --> 00:33:19.040
Rachel, it's great to kind of socialize that with a few people, especially if they're kind

00:33:19.040 --> 00:33:19.839
of at your level.

00:33:20.800 --> 00:33:22.640
And maybe they can help you improve that idea.

00:33:22.640 --> 00:33:26.800
And once you really build that out, then it becomes a good opportunity to scale.

00:33:26.800 --> 00:33:30.800
And you have a network of support around you that can help you build that up.

00:33:31.920 --> 00:33:34.479
And I've seen that play out a lot.

00:33:34.479 --> 00:33:37.760
I don't know if anyone else has had a similar experience in their organization where they

00:33:37.760 --> 00:33:42.479
felt like once they had a good coalition, they were able to get somebody's buy-in.

00:33:42.479 --> 00:33:46.959
But I feel like we don't always talk about the relationships we have either at work or

00:33:46.959 --> 00:33:51.280
in our personal lives and how much of a difference that makes in influencing people to do one

00:33:51.280 --> 00:33:52.400
thing or another.

00:33:52.400 --> 00:33:55.920
So just want to call that out in case that was helpful to people as they're trying to

00:33:55.920 --> 00:33:56.719
pitch new ideas.

00:33:58.800 --> 00:33:59.520
Absolutely.

00:33:59.520 --> 00:34:00.719
Thank you, Rory.

00:34:00.719 --> 00:34:01.439
Yeah, no problem.

00:34:02.400 --> 00:34:05.760
Anybody else have ideas on that topic to share too?

00:34:08.800 --> 00:34:13.679
Yeah, I'll just reinforce we did the same thing when we started our internal user group.

00:34:13.679 --> 00:34:15.760
It was started as just in our user group.

00:34:15.760 --> 00:34:22.399
And it was basically the same five of us that were interested in just presenting back and

00:34:22.399 --> 00:34:27.840
forth to each other each month with very little variety in the presenters.

00:34:28.239 --> 00:34:32.959
But eventually, we started to expand it, started to include other open source languages.

00:34:34.159 --> 00:34:40.320
And now we've literally got hundreds of users across the of the company, pitching new ideas,

00:34:40.320 --> 00:34:41.760
sharing things that they've done.

00:34:41.760 --> 00:34:45.520
And just really cool to have kind of every stage too, right?

00:34:45.520 --> 00:34:50.879
We've got folks who are brand new and have heard of R or Python or something and want

00:34:50.879 --> 00:34:51.439
to learn.

00:34:52.080 --> 00:34:56.719
We've also got people who are super advanced and teaching very complex topics.

00:34:57.679 --> 00:35:00.719
So that kind of snowball effect has worked really well.

00:35:03.439 --> 00:35:04.080
That's awesome.

00:35:04.719 --> 00:35:11.520
I see Abigail, you have started a thread here in the chat here too, if you want to jump

00:35:11.520 --> 00:35:13.679
in and share any perspective there.

00:35:19.120 --> 00:35:22.000
And no worries, I don't want to put anybody on the spot here.

00:35:24.080 --> 00:35:26.399
Yeah, any other thoughts on this?

00:35:27.439 --> 00:35:35.919
I see Ken, you had a question around storytelling.

00:35:35.919 --> 00:35:38.159
Do you want to jump in and ask that to everybody?

00:35:42.080 --> 00:35:47.439
Sure, get myself on video here.

00:35:47.439 --> 00:35:47.679
Yeah.

00:35:49.439 --> 00:35:55.040
You know, I think the discussion going back, I think Mr. Smith was the one who kicked it

00:35:55.040 --> 00:36:01.280
off, really, of how do you get decision makers to buy into your ideas?

00:36:02.320 --> 00:36:08.560
Some of the stuff I'm seeing, I do analyst relations for Posit, so talking with some

00:36:08.560 --> 00:36:13.919
of the market research firms like Gartner and Forrester, there's a lot of research there

00:36:13.919 --> 00:36:18.479
that talks about the use of, you know, the correct use of the right tool to get your

00:36:18.479 --> 00:36:19.040
point across.

00:36:19.760 --> 00:36:26.800
And I wondered if any of you had been taking, you know, data storytelling courses at any

00:36:26.800 --> 00:36:27.120
point.

00:36:27.840 --> 00:36:32.959
Some of you have replied here to help you figure out, you know, what's the right tool

00:36:32.959 --> 00:36:33.600
to get across?

00:36:33.600 --> 00:36:36.239
How do you present data to be able to persuade people?

00:36:37.520 --> 00:36:46.959
And then another point that came up, I thought was also interesting, was the idea of, you

00:36:46.959 --> 00:36:53.840
know, there's this proactive storytelling versus using a self-service method of getting

00:36:53.840 --> 00:36:54.800
your ideas out there.

00:36:54.800 --> 00:37:01.360
So both of those topics, I think are, I find very, very useful.

00:37:01.360 --> 00:37:06.560
And I know that Rachel's found some other customers that, you know, one customer talked

00:37:06.560 --> 00:37:17.439
about using an interactive web app versus sending out a 200-page PDF report and how

00:37:17.439 --> 00:37:20.959
that really changed their interactions with decision makers.

00:37:20.959 --> 00:37:26.719
So just curious to hear more about other people's experiences in that respect.

00:37:30.080 --> 00:37:36.080
I know there was a few people who had thoughts on this in the chat, and Jim, I see you were

00:37:36.080 --> 00:37:36.639
first there.

00:37:36.639 --> 00:37:38.719
Do you want to share any perspective here?

00:37:38.719 --> 00:37:51.679
Just really quickly, I find that we end up going down one of two paths often, depending

00:37:51.679 --> 00:37:56.159
on the client and the environment and the skill sets of the people.

00:37:56.639 --> 00:38:05.760
Sometimes it is, in fact, a matter of storytelling and getting it down into maybe even a five

00:38:05.760 --> 00:38:08.000
minute set of slides.

00:38:09.600 --> 00:38:20.080
But just as often, the exercise is a matter of empowering other analysts or other operational

00:38:20.639 --> 00:38:27.040
people whose day job is doing whatever, and we want to make their life better.

00:38:28.479 --> 00:38:34.239
And so we're going to push data through some kind of a layer to an endpoint so they can

00:38:34.239 --> 00:38:36.320
use it in the system they're comfortable with.

00:38:36.320 --> 00:38:42.320
And so it's more of a, you know, using the endpoint that they're comfortable with, and

00:38:43.040 --> 00:38:51.760
maybe less storytelling, more developing empathy for the person you're trying to help do what

00:38:51.760 --> 00:38:52.399
they do better.

00:38:56.479 --> 00:38:57.439
Thank you.

00:38:57.439 --> 00:38:59.280
I see Marlene, you have your hand raised too.

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:00.639
Want to jump in?

00:39:01.199 --> 00:39:06.560
Yeah, so one, I'm in a master's program right now, and I'm literally in the middle of a

00:39:06.560 --> 00:39:11.600
class that's focused completely around communicating data, which I found admirable.

00:39:11.760 --> 00:39:17.360
They actually spend the time, it's not even, you're not touching data at all in this class.

00:39:17.360 --> 00:39:22.239
They want you to make sure that you identify your target audience, that you use the right

00:39:22.239 --> 00:39:28.000
tone and language, that you make your point easy to follow, things like that, that we

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:31.679
kind of take for granted and are super nuanced, just like presentation giving.

00:39:33.040 --> 00:39:36.560
They force you to really reexamine your habits, use concise language.

00:39:37.040 --> 00:39:43.919
And so I think that goes in line with what the comments made about communicating data.

00:39:43.919 --> 00:39:48.560
It's not just an effective visualization or an effective tool to kind of get the point

00:39:48.560 --> 00:39:52.560
across, but really making sure your words back up your point, right?

00:39:53.520 --> 00:39:58.479
And then secondly, I went to a water data conference out here in Southern California.

00:39:58.479 --> 00:40:00.560
I don't know if anybody else on the call was able to go to this.

00:40:01.280 --> 00:40:04.560
It's called the California Data Conference, but it's all around water, so it's a little

00:40:04.560 --> 00:40:09.600
misleading, but there was an excellent speaker and her name eludes me right now, but she

00:40:09.600 --> 00:40:13.199
gave me an entire presentation that was just gorgeous.

00:40:13.199 --> 00:40:18.719
And it was about highlighting signals so that when you're talking to somebody in management,

00:40:18.719 --> 00:40:23.120
right, that you're not just giving them a bunch of data fluff, that you're really getting

00:40:23.679 --> 00:40:31.600
their attention to the part of the visual that, you know, the outliers or the signal and whatnot.

00:40:31.600 --> 00:40:34.800
And she also referenced a couple of books that I thought were incredible.

00:40:35.679 --> 00:40:38.320
One was, sorry, it's called Signal.

00:40:38.320 --> 00:40:43.280
I believe it's out of print now, but there is a newer version of it, so maybe you can

00:40:43.280 --> 00:40:44.080
hunt it down.

00:40:45.199 --> 00:40:51.360
But yes, I think totally, it's about saying it well, saying it short and concise, saying

00:40:51.360 --> 00:40:56.399
in the language they understand and then giving them the visual to back it up, totally.

00:40:57.120 --> 00:41:01.520
Because usually if you put it in their hands and they get some real visceral feel around

00:41:01.520 --> 00:41:03.120
what the possibility is, it helps.

00:41:03.760 --> 00:41:07.040
But half the time you can't get in the door with them, and that's where probably the other

00:41:07.040 --> 00:41:11.439
half of us who are still in that frustrated kind of vicious cycle of not being able to

00:41:11.439 --> 00:41:18.159
get management to help really build infrastructure or tools or teams to support your work are

00:41:18.159 --> 00:41:18.879
falling into.

00:41:19.439 --> 00:41:21.040
So that's interesting.

00:41:21.040 --> 00:41:23.919
You said it's hard to get in the door with decision makers.

00:41:24.639 --> 00:41:26.159
What makes it hard?

00:41:28.560 --> 00:41:31.760
So some of it is time, right?

00:41:31.760 --> 00:41:37.040
Because there are usually 1,000 other things on their plate that will take more precedent

00:41:37.040 --> 00:41:39.439
than we need our infrastructure updated.

00:41:39.439 --> 00:41:43.760
Like unless your building is on fire, they're never going to see that as something that

00:41:43.760 --> 00:41:45.120
really needs attention.

00:41:45.120 --> 00:41:47.199
At least that's what my organization has been like.

00:41:48.479 --> 00:41:50.639
They're like, our computers still run.

00:41:50.639 --> 00:41:51.840
We're still crunching data.

00:41:51.840 --> 00:41:54.000
Our analysts still do these reports.

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:54.479
We're good.

00:41:55.439 --> 00:41:59.280
We don't need a single source of truth or anything like that, which is crazy.

00:42:00.959 --> 00:42:06.479
And then the other part is even if you get in the door, it's, well, what is the ROI on

00:42:06.479 --> 00:42:07.040
this?

00:42:07.040 --> 00:42:08.479
And sometimes it's hard to do.

00:42:08.479 --> 00:42:10.560
Like I don't have people's salaries.

00:42:10.560 --> 00:42:16.399
I can go to HR or to our accounting and try to get some of those projections, but it also

00:42:16.399 --> 00:42:21.360
seems off-putting to them that this analyst scientist in the corner of the company is

00:42:21.360 --> 00:42:22.800
asking for these things, right?

00:42:22.800 --> 00:42:29.199
So it can be tricky to try to give the value add right up front where they go, aha, I get

00:42:29.199 --> 00:42:29.760
it.

00:42:29.760 --> 00:42:33.840
Instead, you have to kind of say like something's broken and I need to fix it.

00:42:33.840 --> 00:42:37.280
And then you have to prove that it's actually broken enough that it needs fixing.

00:42:37.280 --> 00:42:39.040
So I kind of hope that makes sense.

00:42:39.040 --> 00:42:43.360
But those are kind of the two cases I've run into, both in the same organization.

00:42:46.399 --> 00:42:47.280
Thank you, Marlene.

00:42:47.280 --> 00:42:49.120
That course sounds great, too.

00:42:49.120 --> 00:42:54.879
You're reminding me that I, oh wow, that link is really long, but you're reminding me I

00:42:54.879 --> 00:42:59.520
just bought this everyday business storytelling book and I forgot to actually read it when

00:42:59.520 --> 00:43:00.080
it arrived.

00:43:00.800 --> 00:43:08.639
But one of the lessons learned I saw in it was like in your PowerPoints, like your headers,

00:43:08.639 --> 00:43:09.840
oh, do you have it right there?

00:43:09.840 --> 00:43:11.040
Oh, I see you grabbing a book.

00:43:11.600 --> 00:43:17.040
Like instead of putting like Q3 results or like something that really doesn't mean anything

00:43:17.040 --> 00:43:21.760
at all at the top of your PowerPoint, like actually putting the value there and what

00:43:21.760 --> 00:43:22.959
you're trying to show.

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:26.959
Alan, I see you had some thoughts on this, too.

00:43:26.959 --> 00:43:28.000
Do you want to jump in next?

00:43:33.600 --> 00:43:38.560
And if you change your mind and want to jump in after, let me know.

00:43:38.560 --> 00:43:42.800
Anybody else have any thoughts on the data storytelling piece?

00:43:42.800 --> 00:43:46.320
I think, Adam, you were sharing something about a course you took.

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:52.959
Yeah, if you've ever read the Storytelling with Data book, it's a super great way to think

00:43:52.959 --> 00:43:54.800
about how to distill a graph.

00:43:54.800 --> 00:43:55.439
There it is.

00:43:56.879 --> 00:43:59.919
Yeah, it's like how do you distill the graph down to its essence?

00:44:00.959 --> 00:44:05.520
And the workshop I took with them was really interesting because they really focused hard

00:44:05.520 --> 00:44:08.639
on every graph should just have one big idea.

00:44:09.360 --> 00:44:14.719
And if you're not telling one single individual isolated story with that graphic, it's going

00:44:14.719 --> 00:44:15.679
to confuse people.

00:44:15.679 --> 00:44:20.639
And so you should just keep working on refining that until it's just that one story and then

00:44:20.639 --> 00:44:25.840
make it super obvious what you're actually trying to say with a title that says, you

00:44:25.840 --> 00:44:28.719
know, sales decreased, whatever, you know, last quarter.

00:44:29.760 --> 00:44:30.719
That's the whole story.

00:44:30.719 --> 00:44:37.360
So just being super clear and making sure that each slide, each exhibit is just one

00:44:37.360 --> 00:44:41.439
specific thing you want to get across because people are so bad at juggling what they've

00:44:41.439 --> 00:44:43.679
learned so far in your presentation and what they're looking at now.

00:44:43.679 --> 00:44:47.040
And then thinking about, you know, what they're going to have for lunch.

00:44:47.040 --> 00:44:49.600
And so making it as simple as possible to get that message across.

00:44:50.479 --> 00:44:51.360
Definitely.

00:44:51.360 --> 00:44:56.479
That makes me think about the conversation about like presenting to our executives as

00:44:56.479 --> 00:45:01.360
well, like having one thing in mind when you are meeting with them.

00:45:01.360 --> 00:45:06.159
I have a tendency because you don't get somebody's time all the like as often as

00:45:06.159 --> 00:45:11.120
you want, you want to tell them everything in that like 30 minute meeting instead of

00:45:11.120 --> 00:45:12.000
focusing on one.

00:45:12.560 --> 00:45:13.840
Mike, I see your hand up.

00:45:13.840 --> 00:45:19.600
Yeah, this is just kind of following on from what Adam's just said, though, that yes,

00:45:19.600 --> 00:45:20.239
absolutely.

00:45:20.239 --> 00:45:24.320
I would love if that was the way that we presented data and graphs.

00:45:24.320 --> 00:45:31.040
But there's also the tension that says, well, if anyone takes this graph out of context

00:45:31.040 --> 00:45:36.159
and, you know, copy pastes it and it winds up in front of the CEO and none of the context

00:45:36.159 --> 00:45:40.879
is there because I'm not presenting it, then I must cram every single hedging statement

00:45:40.959 --> 00:45:42.159
onto this graph.

00:45:42.159 --> 00:45:46.479
And so the actual useful stuff becomes like the letterbox in the middle with all of that

00:45:46.479 --> 00:45:47.840
extra fluff.

00:45:49.760 --> 00:45:57.199
I so wish that we could have it so that your graph isn't just a static thing, but it has

00:45:57.199 --> 00:46:03.120
hover overs or whatever else you need to convey that additional contextual information.

00:46:03.919 --> 00:46:10.239
But I think the danger is that people try and have a graph that meets the needs of 15

00:46:10.239 --> 00:46:11.040
different parties.

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:17.040
For slides that have a button, what's your business function?

00:46:17.040 --> 00:46:20.000
Click that and then it's going to fill everything in for you based on that function.

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:21.679
And it might say, no, you can't see this.

00:46:22.719 --> 00:46:23.199
That's right.

00:46:25.360 --> 00:46:27.120
Or at best, call me.

00:46:27.120 --> 00:46:28.000
It's complicated.

00:46:31.280 --> 00:46:38.000
Well, actually, do you always put your contact information on graphs and slides you put out?

00:46:40.399 --> 00:46:41.360
Does anybody do that?

00:46:43.919 --> 00:46:44.419
No.

00:46:45.360 --> 00:46:47.040
Yeah, the idea though.

00:46:47.040 --> 00:46:48.239
Yeah, it's complicated.

00:46:49.040 --> 00:46:52.959
I worked for an organization that did always have like every dashboard and thing had a

00:46:52.959 --> 00:46:59.280
thing, like you, somebody to contact within the organization that made it or who owns

00:46:59.280 --> 00:47:00.000
the data behind it.

00:47:01.439 --> 00:47:06.479
I started doing that on like random Google Docs that I share across the company, like

00:47:06.479 --> 00:47:09.040
making sure that my name is at the top of it.

00:47:09.040 --> 00:47:14.959
So if anybody has questions, they know who originally made this and to reach out to me.

00:47:15.919 --> 00:47:22.399
I had a leader a couple of years ago ask if we could put QR codes next to the plots that

00:47:22.399 --> 00:47:26.239
we put in a slide as a way for people to get in touch with more information.

00:47:26.239 --> 00:47:28.879
And sure enough, there's an RPAG that doesn't make QR codes.

00:47:28.879 --> 00:47:29.919
So there you go.

00:47:33.120 --> 00:47:38.560
I see somebody had asked a question anonymously that was, no matter how much I practice, I

00:47:38.560 --> 00:47:40.959
always panic when I have a presentation.

00:47:40.959 --> 00:47:44.639
Does anybody have tips you would like to share regarding public speaking?

00:47:46.320 --> 00:47:47.520
Yeah, I have a quick one.

00:47:47.520 --> 00:47:48.719
Do a podcast.

00:47:48.719 --> 00:47:49.360
I'm kidding.

00:47:49.360 --> 00:47:49.919
I'm kidding.

00:47:49.919 --> 00:47:51.760
It actually did help me though, honestly.

00:47:53.600 --> 00:47:57.439
So it would be unnatural not to feel nervous, right?

00:47:58.560 --> 00:47:59.600
Everyone feels nervous.

00:47:59.600 --> 00:48:02.239
Even the people that don't look as though they're nervous are nervous.

00:48:02.239 --> 00:48:03.840
It's just they're managing those nerves.

00:48:04.479 --> 00:48:12.159
And the other thing I tend to think of is, you know, you talk to people as though you're

00:48:12.159 --> 00:48:14.000
just having a conversation with friends.

00:48:15.120 --> 00:48:21.360
You know, don't use language that is more complex than you would normally use or, you know,

00:48:23.120 --> 00:48:27.040
I know some people work well with, they kind of put on a persona or put on a hat

00:48:27.840 --> 00:48:29.199
in order to present.

00:48:29.199 --> 00:48:34.080
But honestly, I tend to like just picking out one or two people in the audience and

00:48:34.080 --> 00:48:35.919
just talk to them like I was having a conversation.

00:48:39.199 --> 00:48:40.560
Caitlin, I see you have your hand raised.

00:48:42.320 --> 00:48:44.239
Yeah, Mike, those were really great points.

00:48:45.199 --> 00:48:46.479
I feel like I can talk about this.

00:48:46.479 --> 00:48:49.520
I just finished a one hour workshop at a conference.

00:48:51.120 --> 00:48:56.879
So I think the biggest tip, and yeah, you hit the nail on the head, like it's, of course,

00:48:56.879 --> 00:48:57.679
you're going to be nervous.

00:48:58.000 --> 00:48:59.919
30 minutes before my hands were sweating.

00:48:59.919 --> 00:49:03.679
I was like, oh, gosh, like, am I going to completely blank?

00:49:03.679 --> 00:49:04.000
Right.

00:49:04.000 --> 00:49:11.120
But no, I think once you so something I do is like, I count myself down because really,

00:49:11.120 --> 00:49:14.479
it only takes like one second of courage because once you're once you're up there, you can't

00:49:14.479 --> 00:49:15.199
really go back.

00:49:15.840 --> 00:49:19.120
So it's like in my head, I kind of like three, two, one, go.

00:49:19.679 --> 00:49:21.520
And then, you know, you go.

00:49:21.520 --> 00:49:29.679
And I think during the start of my, I guess, public speaking engagements or career, I did

00:49:29.679 --> 00:49:33.120
kind of put on a persona and stuff.

00:49:33.120 --> 00:49:41.520
But now that I've done it more and more, like, it's your best bet to just be yourself and

00:49:41.520 --> 00:49:43.600
talk to the audience.

00:49:43.600 --> 00:49:45.360
And I think it's so important to remember.

00:49:45.360 --> 00:49:51.600
I feel like public speaking, it's so easy to just focus on yourself and how, you know,

00:49:51.600 --> 00:49:53.520
maybe perceived by the audience this and that.

00:49:53.520 --> 00:49:57.439
But like most of the time, the audience is just there to learn.

00:49:57.439 --> 00:50:02.399
So in whatever way you can provide value without like just being so in your head about what

00:50:02.399 --> 00:50:06.239
you look like, what you sound like, what content you're even presenting.

00:50:06.800 --> 00:50:10.800
Yeah, I think it's so important just to remember why the audience is there and they're there

00:50:10.800 --> 00:50:11.280
to learn.

00:50:11.280 --> 00:50:11.840
Right.

00:50:11.840 --> 00:50:17.120
And then the one last thing that I could say about public speaking that's really helped

00:50:17.120 --> 00:50:23.760
me is if you are doing a public speaking engagement, do something that on a topic that you feel

00:50:23.760 --> 00:50:27.600
very comfortable talking about, that you could talk on this topic for hours and hours and

00:50:27.600 --> 00:50:27.840
hours.

00:50:27.840 --> 00:50:32.719
Because I've done presentations where I didn't really feel super confident about the topic.

00:50:32.719 --> 00:50:40.399
Like once I did a workshop on data visualizations, and though I had spent the whole year not

00:50:40.399 --> 00:50:45.760
making a data visualization at all, I was just doing data analysis pipelines in R.

00:50:45.760 --> 00:50:46.239
Right.

00:50:46.239 --> 00:50:51.199
So that public speaking engagement, I remember I was so nervous because I didn't feel so

00:50:51.199 --> 00:50:53.120
confident on the topic I was presenting.

00:50:53.120 --> 00:50:57.199
So yeah, just make sure you know your topic really well.

00:50:57.199 --> 00:51:00.639
And then I think from there, it can flow really natural.

00:51:02.719 --> 00:51:03.919
Those are all great points.

00:51:04.879 --> 00:51:10.159
What you were saying, Kaylin, was just making me think about sometimes it has been helpful

00:51:10.159 --> 00:51:15.439
for me is to reach out to a few people who I know are going to be there ahead of time

00:51:15.439 --> 00:51:22.239
and just asking them maybe questions about what they would like to learn or, I don't

00:51:22.239 --> 00:51:24.879
know, just reaching out to them in general to talk to them.

00:51:24.879 --> 00:51:30.479
Because then I at least know part of what I'm providing or sharing is providing value

00:51:30.479 --> 00:51:32.080
to somebody in the audience.

00:51:32.080 --> 00:51:34.560
And it makes me a lot less nervous.

00:51:34.560 --> 00:51:39.600
I guess also helps with any sort of imposter syndrome, too, to know that this is going

00:51:39.600 --> 00:51:41.919
to be valuable for at least these people.

00:51:41.919 --> 00:51:45.679
So chances are it will be valuable for their other peers there, too.

00:51:46.800 --> 00:51:47.760
Yeah, no, for sure.

00:51:47.760 --> 00:51:53.199
And even yesterday, I was talking, so I presented today and then the conference was yesterday

00:51:53.199 --> 00:51:53.600
and today.

00:51:53.600 --> 00:51:56.399
And I was talking to people who registered for my workshop.

00:51:56.399 --> 00:51:58.159
And that made me feel so much better.

00:51:58.159 --> 00:52:02.719
And even seeing them today in the audience, those were the ones that I was looking at

00:52:02.719 --> 00:52:03.919
and talking to, you know what I mean?

00:52:05.679 --> 00:52:06.320
Absolutely.

00:52:06.320 --> 00:52:10.560
I was just talking with one of my co-workers who's going to a PyData conference about this,

00:52:10.560 --> 00:52:17.120
too, and was just saying, like, if we do have, like, a list of who is attending and if you

00:52:17.120 --> 00:52:21.199
can, like, reach out to somebody on LinkedIn ahead of time or just introduce yourself,

00:52:21.840 --> 00:52:27.199
it makes you feel so much more comfortable when you're there that you at least know somebody.

00:52:30.159 --> 00:52:32.399
Any other thoughts or tips?

00:52:36.320 --> 00:52:41.199
I really liked Anasa's tip about dressing comfortably, like, dress in something that

00:52:41.199 --> 00:52:44.639
you're comfortable wearing and that you're not going to be constantly thinking about

00:52:44.639 --> 00:52:45.360
what you're wearing.

00:52:46.959 --> 00:52:47.919
That's super important.

00:52:48.800 --> 00:52:49.280
Absolutely.

00:52:49.280 --> 00:52:53.120
Yeah, I've noticed that, like, if I have a presentation to do, I'll pick an outfit that

00:52:53.120 --> 00:52:54.159
makes me very comfortable.

00:52:54.159 --> 00:52:58.399
I'll even get a haircut or I'll do something like just those are little things that will

00:52:58.399 --> 00:53:02.239
definitely make you, yeah, make you feel better.

00:53:03.760 --> 00:53:06.000
Yeah, minimize all the other stuff.

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:10.239
The peripheral stuff that could make you nervous, that's not you speaking, because

00:53:10.239 --> 00:53:11.360
you don't need that in your life.

00:53:12.159 --> 00:53:13.360
You're already nervous enough.

00:53:15.760 --> 00:53:16.399
Absolutely.

00:53:16.399 --> 00:53:18.479
I see a few people talking about Toastmasters.

00:53:18.479 --> 00:53:20.959
Has anybody been part of Toastmasters?

00:53:23.120 --> 00:53:24.159
I'm seeing some nods.

00:53:24.800 --> 00:53:25.360
Never been.

00:53:27.520 --> 00:53:32.560
A lot of places will let you drop in if you want to go to a group and say, like, hey,

00:53:32.560 --> 00:53:35.600
I'm interested, but I'm not sure if I want to do this.

00:53:35.760 --> 00:53:39.919
A lot of them are really happy to have you spectate and kind of clap for people when

00:53:39.919 --> 00:53:41.120
they finish and stuff like that.

00:53:41.120 --> 00:53:42.879
So I recommend anybody go check it out.

00:53:42.879 --> 00:53:44.320
But it's usually not data focused.

00:53:44.320 --> 00:53:47.280
There's a good topic each time, each session.

00:53:47.280 --> 00:53:49.040
It's not data, but helpful.

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:50.399
Cool.

00:53:50.399 --> 00:53:54.560
I've done super technical data talks to them, and it's kind of helpful because talking to

00:53:54.560 --> 00:54:01.199
an audience has no idea what your domain knowledge is can make you like, oh, OK, I have to, like,

00:54:01.199 --> 00:54:03.280
make sure this jargon is to a minimum.

00:54:03.679 --> 00:54:08.320
I have to explain this like I'm explaining it to a really smart junior high student instead

00:54:08.320 --> 00:54:09.679
of my peers.

00:54:09.679 --> 00:54:12.000
So it can be really helpful.

00:54:12.000 --> 00:54:19.600
They also have, like, a meeting is an hour, and they will have three scheduled big presentations,

00:54:19.600 --> 00:54:20.959
like, 15, 20 minutes.

00:54:20.959 --> 00:54:22.560
But they also have little drills.

00:54:22.560 --> 00:54:26.000
And even as a first timer, you can go and try one of the little drills where you get

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:30.959
up for 30 seconds, and they ask you something, and you just have to speak off the cuff.

00:54:30.959 --> 00:54:32.800
And it kind of works out some of those jitters.

00:54:33.360 --> 00:54:37.520
Even if you're introverted, even if you're scared, it's worth doing, because if it doesn't

00:54:37.520 --> 00:54:38.800
scare you, it won't change you, right?

00:54:39.439 --> 00:54:40.399
Totally worth doing, though.

00:54:40.399 --> 00:54:43.679
I wish to go to one Toastmaster meeting in their life, I'd say.

00:54:44.320 --> 00:54:44.820
Cool.

00:54:45.760 --> 00:54:53.919
We had for the Posit conference, all the accepted speakers get speaker training through articulation.

00:54:53.919 --> 00:54:56.639
So I got to go through that last year.

00:54:56.639 --> 00:55:02.159
And it was really helpful to think about, like, starting off your talk with a story,

00:55:02.239 --> 00:55:05.199
like, framing things as a story to bring the audience in.

00:55:06.800 --> 00:55:11.679
And I've been starting to try and do that with presentations that I give internally as well.

00:55:11.679 --> 00:55:15.280
Like, who is the customer that this is impacting?

00:55:15.280 --> 00:55:17.919
And why am I presenting this to?

00:55:19.600 --> 00:55:22.719
Jared, I see you had asked a question in the chat a little bit earlier.

00:55:22.719 --> 00:55:24.560
I'm sorry we didn't get to it until now.

00:55:24.560 --> 00:55:25.360
Do you want to jump in?

00:55:29.439 --> 00:55:30.560
And Jared, I'll read.

00:55:30.560 --> 00:55:31.199
Oh, I can see you.

00:55:31.199 --> 00:55:31.760
I'm muted.

00:55:31.760 --> 00:55:32.639
There you go.

00:55:32.639 --> 00:55:33.120
Am I there?

00:55:33.120 --> 00:55:34.000
Can you guys hear me?

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:34.500
Yes.

00:55:34.879 --> 00:55:35.379
Sure.

00:55:35.760 --> 00:55:42.000
This is just more open-ended for anybody's experience when it comes to giving presentations

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:46.239
or, I mean, I know it has more to do with the audience that you're in front of.

00:55:46.239 --> 00:55:53.520
But trying to avoid the sales pitch type of presentation versus keeping things much more

00:55:53.520 --> 00:56:01.199
unbiased and just presenting, kind of giving an unbiased approach to what you're presenting

00:56:01.199 --> 00:56:03.439
instead of trying to push an agenda, essentially.

00:56:03.439 --> 00:56:11.520
Because I've gone both ways where if I'm trying to essentially persuade decision makers on,

00:56:11.520 --> 00:56:17.679
you know, my idea or pitch my idea, then it obviously becomes straight into a sales pitch

00:56:17.679 --> 00:56:18.719
kind of scenario.

00:56:18.719 --> 00:56:26.959
But I've also, like, tried to just do presentations on giving the information in sort of a very

00:56:27.040 --> 00:56:31.199
unbiased, disseminating the information to the public audience type scenario.

00:56:31.199 --> 00:56:41.040
And I always run the gambit of, like, how to not include your own personal bias when

00:56:41.040 --> 00:56:45.679
presenting and try to keep things very open, if that makes sense.

00:56:45.679 --> 00:56:47.520
Just wanted to kind of get everybody's opinion.

00:56:52.080 --> 00:56:54.719
Anybody have thoughts to share there?

00:56:57.919 --> 00:56:59.679
I kind of want Jim to explain himself.

00:57:03.120 --> 00:57:08.639
I, again, we're kind of tool people and maybe even statisticians here.

00:57:09.360 --> 00:57:13.679
What we bring in terms of our backgrounds and skills matters.

00:57:14.639 --> 00:57:25.760
And so, more often than not, the opening slide is going to say who we are and process we

00:57:26.399 --> 00:57:29.439
maybe use to arrive at this piece of information.

00:57:29.439 --> 00:57:31.679
And that's a pitch, you know.

00:57:33.520 --> 00:57:40.639
Now, bias maybe implies that we've imprinted something unnatural or a distortion on this.

00:57:40.639 --> 00:57:45.919
And I don't, you know, mean to misconstrue what you said there.

00:57:45.919 --> 00:57:54.800
But I don't undersell the skills we bring as people to the conversations with, you know,

00:57:54.800 --> 00:57:59.679
our organizations, you know, whether it's a government institution or charity or a business.

00:58:00.560 --> 00:58:06.080
We bring something that's valuable and hugely valuable, in fact.

00:58:06.080 --> 00:58:11.760
So, we shouldn't be ashamed to, you know, to imprint that on the work we've done

00:58:11.760 --> 00:58:15.679
and the results that we've arrived at.

00:58:15.679 --> 00:58:17.760
At least that's kind of where I'm coming from.

00:58:21.520 --> 00:58:22.479
Great points, Jim.

00:58:22.479 --> 00:58:22.959
Thank you.

00:58:25.439 --> 00:58:30.719
Thank you all so much for joining today and kind of winging it with us.

00:58:31.360 --> 00:58:32.479
This has been really fun.

00:58:32.479 --> 00:58:37.520
I appreciate everybody jumping in here and being the featured leader, too.

